===Etymology===
Old English ''[[sweord]]'', from {{proto|Germanic|swerðan}} (cf. West Frisian {{term|swurd|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|zwaard}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Schwert}}), from {{proto|Indo-European|su̯r̥dhom}} (compare Old Church Slavonic {{term|svĭrdĭlŭ}} 'drill'), from *''su̯eros'' (compare {{etyl|goh|-}} ''swero'' 'body pain', ''sweren'' 'to fester', {{etyl|cy|-}} ''chwerw'' 'bitter, sharp', ''chwarren'' 'ulcer', {{etyl|ru|-}} {{term|хворый|tr=xvóryj||sick|lang=ru}}, {{etyl|ae|-}} ''x<sup>v</sup>ara'' 'wound').

